  "worklog": "# brainTrade Work Log\n*Check this anytime to see what I'm doing and how I'm thinking.*\n\n## 2026-05-02 01:04 UTC \u2014 [Pillar 2] The OBI boost sleeve is anti-edge, while first-trade weakness is real but still too thin to force a cooldown\n\n**Task:** Audit the latest PM smart-entry outcome sample to see whether the OBI-based V5b shadow sizing or the V6 cooldown idea deserved promotion into live logic.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive (`pm-bot`, `hl-bot`).\n- Rotation pointed to **P2**.\n- In the recent `v5a_pass` sample (`2026-04-01+`, **23 trades**), the OBI boost sleeve is the weakest pocket, not the strongest:\n  - `BOOST`: **2 trades, 0.0% WR, -1.000 avg pnl_pct**\n  - `REDUCE_MILD_BEAR`: **3 trades, 33.3% WR, -0.346 avg pnl_pct**\n  - `NORMAL`: **6 trades, 83.3% WR, +0.606 avg pnl_pct**\n- The cooldown shadow did **not** validate a generic 10-minute gate:\n  - `FIRST`: **3 trades, 0.0% WR, -1.000 avg pnl_pct**\n  - `PASS`: **9 trades, 66.7% WR, +0.292 avg pnl_pct**\n  - `BLOCK`: **11 trades, 72.7% WR, +0.404 avg pnl_pct**\n- So the leak is not \u201ctrades too close together.\u201d The uglier pocket is the **first trade** of a sequence/session.\n- Price context still says the relaxed floor below **0.51** is weak (**3 trades, 33.3% WR, -0.340 avg pnl_pct**), but that evidence is thinner than the OBI result.\n- I wrote the artifact to `/home/ubuntu/clawd/research/p2-obi-shadow-audit-2026-05-02.md`.\n\n**My thinking:** The cleanest P2 edge here was rejecting the wrong promotion. If heavy bearish OBI really improved PM entries, the `BOOST` bucket should have outperformed `NORMAL`; instead it got wrecked. Meanwhile the cooldown data says a blunt 10-minute lock would have cut too many winners. The more interesting pattern is opening-noise risk on `FIRST` trades, but that still needs a few more tagged examples before I hard-code a guard.\n\n**Decision:** Keep the OBI boost **out** of live sizing, do **not** enable a generic 10-minute cooldown, and keep first-trade weakness as the next watchlist variable instead of overreacting to a small sample.\n\n**Next:** On the next Pillar 2 pass, isolate `FIRST` trades by hour and copy-regime once the new copy fields populate, then test whether the real leak is specifically `FIRST + 11 UTC` rather than cooldown spacing in general.\n\n## 2026-05-01 21:04 UTC \u2014 [Pillar 1] BTC headcount stayed bullish, but one whale short almost erased the whole notional edge\n\n**Task:** Run a fresh Pillar 1 leaderboard scan, compare it with the last BTC-bullish rescan, and decide whether the bullish copy-intel read still held.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive (`pm-bot`, `hl-bot`).\n- Rotation pointed to **P1**.\n- Fresh HL tracker printed **BTC 7L/2S, ETH 3L/5S, SOL 2L/6S**, but headcount was misleading again.\n- BTC is no longer a clean whale-long book. Current notional is only **$29.38M long vs $28.15M short** \u2192 net just **+$1.23M long**.\n- The main reversal came from **anon-0x61ce** reopening a huge bearish block: **BTC SHORT $21.99M** and **ETH SHORT $15.99M**",
